prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We will perform our observations in the lowest-resolution spectral mode, but ask to not collapse the data cubes in order to retain the information necessary for searches for lines emission in our galaxies. Band 7 was chosen as it optimizes search for line (CO, C+) emission transitions for z=4-5 SMGs.
As outlined in the science justification a resolution of 0.2'' is key to reach the science goals of this proposal.

We propose to perform band 7 continuum observations at ~0.2'' resolution toward 39 SMGs with F(230GHz)>1.65mJy/beam in the COSMOS field (LST 10hr), drawn from the AzTEC/ASTE 1.1 mm SMG sample survey followed-up, and detected within our ALMA Cycle 2 follow-up at 230GHz. Assuming beta=1.5 the source fluxes at 275GHz are estimated to be a factor of 1.85 higher than at 230GHz (PI: Karim). Thus, an rms of 0.11 mJy will allow us to detect our faintest sources at 7sigma, even if they break up into 4 components. This can be achieved in 4 hours total time. ALMA is the only instrument available for this project as observations of such a large sample would require unfeasible amounts of observation time using other facilities.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The SMGs has been invigorated in the last years thanks to the advent of new-generation interferometers, in particular ALMA. The next crucial step in the endeavor to understand SMGs is toward constraining the physical properties of SMGs across cosmic time and their role in galaxy evolution. To achieve this determining the sizes, multiplicity and clumpiness of SMGs on 1-2kpc scales is key, and possible only now with ALMA observations. To achieve this, we request 4hr of ALMA telescope time at 350 GHz to target the brightest 39 SMGs drawn from the 1.1mm AzTEC/ASTE sample in the inner 0.72sq.deg. of the COSMOS field with S/N(230GHz)>15 ALMA detections, with a median redshift of 2.85, and with unmatched multi-wavelength coverage. The observations are the still missing link to robustly determine i) the morphological composition (disentangling clumpy/smooth and/or merging nature) of the sources across cosmic time, ii) the (sub)mm galaxy counts at the bright end, and thus their cosmic evolution and contribution to the cosmic star formation history, and iii) the evolutionary connection between SMGs and red galaxies.
